[SPEAKER_00] And I thank Ricardo Lago for mentioning this to me.

173
00:18:46,380 --> 00:18:52,380
[SPEAKER_00] In the war time, we basically conscripted a large part of the population and sent them overseas.

174
00:18:52,380 --> 00:19:00,380
[SPEAKER_00] In this war, we conscripted a large fraction of the workforce and asked them to stay at home as kind of an investment in public health.

175
00:19:00,380 --> 00:19:02,380
[SPEAKER_00] It's kind of the analog.

176
00:19:05,380 --> 00:19:06,380
[SPEAKER_00] What was needed?

177
00:19:06,380 --> 00:19:13,380
[SPEAKER_00] What type of fiscal and monetary policies would you recommend for an economy that's hit by these types of shocks?

178
00:19:13,380 --> 00:19:19,380
[SPEAKER_00] I think it's very clear the first thing you want to make sure is the financial system is on sound footing.

179
00:19:20,380 --> 00:19:29,380
[SPEAKER_00] So you want to make sure that the central bank stands ready to lend financial support, to mitigate, you know, the excessive fear, perhaps, that people might have.

180
00:19:29,380 --> 00:19:31,380
[SPEAKER_00] People are very afraid of what might happen.

181
00:19:31,380 --> 00:19:35,380
[SPEAKER_00] So you definitely want financial stability measures.

182
00:19:35,380 --> 00:19:41,380
[SPEAKER_00] The second thing I think you'd want is some form of social insurance.

183
00:19:42,380 --> 00:19:45,380
[SPEAKER_00] You do not want economic stimulus, I would say.

184
00:19:45,380 --> 00:19:54,380
[SPEAKER_00] And this is the part where I think it's important to understand that this was not like a financial, the aggregate demand shock of the financial crisis.

185
00:19:54,380 --> 00:19:59,380
[SPEAKER_00] We actually wanted to, in some sense, we wanted output to contract.

186
00:19:59,380 --> 00:20:02,380
[SPEAKER_00] We wanted employment to contract.

187
00:20:03,380 --> 00:20:07,380
[SPEAKER_00] And the idea of stimulating the economy when you're wanting it to contract seems incongruent.

188
00:20:07,380 --> 00:20:12,380
[SPEAKER_00] So you want social insurance for sure.

189
00:20:12,380 --> 00:20:17,380
[SPEAKER_00] As I mentioned, the effects, the ill effects of the shock were disproportionately felt.

190
00:20:17,380 --> 00:20:29,380
[SPEAKER_00] We did not want to repeat what happened during the recovery dynamic of the last crisis where the perception was that the financial system got bailed out,

191
00:20:30,380 --> 00:20:34,380
[SPEAKER_00] and homeowner was essentially left to flail in the foreclosure winds at the time.

192
00:20:34,380 --> 00:20:36,380
[SPEAKER_00] It was just not good.

193
00:20:36,380 --> 00:20:37,380
[SPEAKER_00] It's not good along many dimensions.

194
00:20:37,380 --> 00:20:39,380
[SPEAKER_00] It's not right, I don't think.

195
00:20:39,380 --> 00:20:48,380
[SPEAKER_00] But it also wasn't good very politically because it fostered this, it contributed to this political polarization in the United States.

196
00:20:48,380 --> 00:20:50,380
[SPEAKER_00] So what do you need?

197
00:20:50,380 --> 00:20:57,380
[SPEAKER_00] I mean, what type of policies would be called for if this type of redistribution, this social insurance, this helping our fellow citizens,

198
00:20:58,380 --> 00:20:59,380
[SPEAKER_00] and if it's desirable?

199
00:20:59,380 --> 00:21:09,380
[SPEAKER_00] I mean, it seems clear you'd want a targeted, well-designed targeted transfer program that would target, you know, those individuals and businesses that were most ill-affected by the shock.

200
00:21:09,380 --> 00:21:18,380
[SPEAKER_00] And then there's the question of how would you finance such a redistribution, especially in light of contracting output.

201
00:21:19,380 --> 00:21:27,380
[SPEAKER_00] And the answer there is, well, I mean, there's probably several ways you can think about financing these desired transfers.

202
00:21:27,380 --> 00:21:40,380
[SPEAKER_00] One way might have been a temporary surtax, like a VAT, for example, that was elevated for a temporary period of time to help finance the endeavor that society judged to be desirable.

203
00:21:42,380 --> 00:21:43,380
[SPEAKER_00] What did we get?

204
00:21:43,380 --> 00:21:44,380
[SPEAKER_00] What did we get?

205
00:21:44,380 --> 00:21:45,380
[SPEAKER_00] In the United States, at least.

206
00:21:45,380 --> 00:21:50,380
[SPEAKER_00] Well, what we got was we got the financial stability measures that are kind of essential.

207
00:21:50,380 --> 00:21:56,380
[SPEAKER_00] At the Fed, I was very, you know, I gave the Fed A-plus on this, grade A marks.

208
00:21:56,380 --> 00:22:02,380
[SPEAKER_00] I mean, in my view, I mean, many of the emergency lending facilities we set up were not even used.

209
00:22:03,380 --> 00:22:10,380
[SPEAKER_00] But just the mere establishment of the facility seemed enough to calm nerves in private bond markets, for example.

210
00:22:10,380 --> 00:22:15,380
[SPEAKER_00] So I give the Fed A-plus along that dimension.

211
00:22:15,380 --> 00:22:19,380
[SPEAKER_00] What did we get in terms of social insurance?

212
00:22:19,380 --> 00:22:26,380
[SPEAKER_00] Well, we got the two really big fiscal packages was the CARES Act under the previous administration,

213
00:22:26,380 --> 00:22:30,380
[SPEAKER_00] and then the American Rescue Plan under the current administration.

214
00:22:31,380 --> 00:22:37,380
[SPEAKER_00] You know, these transfers were largely targeted to the bottom half of the distribution.

215
00:22:37,380 --> 00:22:40,380
[SPEAKER_00] I didn't receive any money.

216
00:22:40,380 --> 00:22:42,380
[SPEAKER_00] I got to work from home.

217
00:22:42,380 --> 00:22:43,380
[SPEAKER_00] I was very fortunate.

218
00:22:43,380 --> 00:22:49,380
[SPEAKER_00] The money basically went where it was supposed to go broadly.

219
00:22:49,380 --> 00:22:59,380
[SPEAKER_00] You had the PPP loans that were designed to support small businesses, you know, but that basically did what it was supposed to do as well, in my view.

220
00:23:00,380 --> 00:23:03,380
[SPEAKER_00] Now, the implementation was sloppy.

221
00:23:03,380 --> 00:23:08,380
[SPEAKER_00] It was a considerable amount of fraud as well, as you might expect when these packages are put together and it's a war.

222
00:23:08,380 --> 00:23:10,380
[SPEAKER_00] I mean, you don't have time to fine tune these things.

223
00:23:10,380 --> 00:23:18,380
[SPEAKER_00] And also, we were very cognizant of kind of underdoing it at the previous crisis.

224
00:23:18,380 --> 00:23:24,380
[SPEAKER_00] And, you know, if you underdo it, you're going to have to live with the political consequences for a long time.

225
00:23:25,380 --> 00:23:28,380
[SPEAKER_00] So it was viewed that overdoing it, if anything, was the way to go.

226
00:23:28,380 --> 00:23:30,380
[SPEAKER_00] But this was known beforehand.

227
00:23:30,380 --> 00:23:35,380
[SPEAKER_00] You know, this is -- and then how was it financed?

228
00:23:35,380 --> 00:23:38,380
[SPEAKER_00] Well, we don't have a VAT in the United States.

229
00:23:38,380 --> 00:23:46,380
[SPEAKER_00] And in any case, it would probably have been politically infeasible to actually finance it in that way in the short time that was needed to pass the legislation.

230
00:23:46,380 --> 00:23:52,380
[SPEAKER_00] So the way we financed it was, you know, really through the inflation tax.

231
00:23:52,380 --> 00:23:56,380
[SPEAKER_00] I mean, you've got to finance it some way.

232
00:23:56,380 --> 00:24:02,380
[SPEAKER_00] If these transfers are desirable and necessary, which I argue most people would have argued yes, you've got to finance it some way.

233
00:24:02,380 --> 00:24:05,380
[SPEAKER_00] If not a direct tax, it's got to be some other tax.

234
00:24:05,380 --> 00:24:11,380
[SPEAKER_00] So I have a very, very different view about the desirability of the inflation that we've experienced.

235
00:24:11,380 --> 00:24:16,380
[SPEAKER_00] I actually interpret it as a constrained second best public finance measure.

236
00:24:17,380 --> 00:24:25,380
[SPEAKER_00] And that any attempt to fight that tax from emerging would have had much, much worse consequences for what happened.

237
00:24:25,380 --> 00:24:32,380
[SPEAKER_00] So I think we really need to give a pause here about how we interpret the inflation that we've recently experienced.

238
00:24:32,380 --> 00:24:39,380
[SPEAKER_00] On the other hand, even at the Fed at the time, I was not in favor of cutting interest rates.

239
00:24:40,380 --> 00:24:46,380
[SPEAKER_00] It's in line with Michael Woodford, who wrote a paper at the time, saying this type of shock does not require a cut in interest rates.

240
00:24:46,380 --> 00:24:49,380
[SPEAKER_00] This is not a time to stimulate demand.

241
00:24:49,380 --> 00:24:55,380
[SPEAKER_00] This is a time for social insurance, and the CARES Act at the time was doing that.

242
00:24:55,380 --> 00:25:00,380
[SPEAKER_00] And so I give the Fed an F on this dimension.

243
00:25:00,380 --> 00:25:01,380
[SPEAKER_00] So there you go.

244
00:25:01,380 --> 00:25:06,380
[SPEAKER_00] Even at the Fed, I was praising it and also criticizing it at the same time.

245
00:25:06,380 --> 00:25:17,380
[SPEAKER_00] So this was an unneeded measure, and I think it primarily manifests itself, I'd say, in elevated asset prices that have subsequently been reversed.

246
00:25:17,380 --> 00:25:21,380
[SPEAKER_00] Here's the inflation experience in the United States.

247
00:25:21,380 --> 00:25:25,380
[SPEAKER_00] This is PCE inflation, the official headline measure that the Fed uses.

248
00:25:25,380 --> 00:25:28,380
[SPEAKER_00] The orange line is the month-over-month annualized inflation rate.

249
00:25:28,380 --> 00:25:30,380
[SPEAKER_00] The blue line is the year-over-year measure.

250
00:25:30,380 --> 00:25:35,380
[SPEAKER_00] You see this, basically, the year-over-year measure is basically nicely hump-shaped.

251
00:25:35,380 --> 00:25:50,380
[SPEAKER_00] I'd argue that if you were to actually run an optimal public finance simulation in a real business cycle model that was designed, you know, wanted to finance, say, an optimal transfer policy through a VAT,

252
00:25:50,380 --> 00:25:54,380
[SPEAKER_00] that the optimal tax would have likely looked something like this.

253
00:25:54,380 --> 00:26:04,380
[SPEAKER_00] You know, consumers would have been complaining about the increase in cost of living, that the taxes are higher, they're making the goods more expensive, but at the same time, there's no free lunch.

254
00:26:04,380 --> 00:26:11,380
[SPEAKER_00] You have to finance the endeavor in some manner, whether it's a direct tax or inflation.

255
00:26:11,380 --> 00:26:14,380
[SPEAKER_00] It happened through the inflation tax in the United States.

256
00:26:14,380 --> 00:26:17,380
[SPEAKER_00] Was the inflation avoidable?

257
00:26:17,380 --> 00:26:18,380
[SPEAKER_00] Yes, of course it was avoidable.

258
00:26:18,380 --> 00:26:19,380
[SPEAKER_00] Of course it was avoidable.

259
00:26:19,380 --> 00:26:29,380
[SPEAKER_00] But think about the types of policies that would have been necessary to avoid the inflation, and then think about how these very real shocks would have had to manifest themselves.

260
00:26:29,380 --> 00:26:32,380
[SPEAKER_00] It's not like there's a free lunch here.

261
00:26:32,380 --> 00:26:48,380
[SPEAKER_00] If you would have kept inflation stable, I mean, it's quite likely, I think, that you would have seen unemployment spike up very high and remain high for a very, very long time, and then people would be complaining about the ill state of the labor market, etc.

262
00:26:48,380 --> 00:26:55,380
[SPEAKER_00] So here's the inflation unemployment rate experience for the United States since the last crisis.

263
00:26:55,380 --> 00:27:03,380
[SPEAKER_00] We see that, you know, in the last crisis, the unemployment rate remained elevated and came down very, very slowly.

264
00:27:03,380 --> 00:27:05,380
[SPEAKER_00] It was a painfully slow recovery.

265
00:27:05,380 --> 00:27:10,380
[SPEAKER_00] And again, this was in response to a completely fabricated shock in the financial sector.

266
00:27:10,380 --> 00:27:13,380
[SPEAKER_00] There was no real shock at the time.

267
00:27:13,380 --> 00:27:17,380
[SPEAKER_00] Take a look at the spike in unemployment in March of 2020.

268
00:27:17,380 --> 00:27:32,380
[SPEAKER_00] I'm telling you, I think most of you know, I mean, if you're sitting there in March of 2020, and you were to ask most Americans whether they would take this recovery dynamic with the cost of this bump in inflation, my guess is most Americans would have taken it.

269
00:27:32,380 --> 00:27:37,380
[SPEAKER_00] I mean, this is borderline miraculous recovery as far as I'm concerned.

270
00:27:37,380 --> 00:27:44,380
[SPEAKER_00] And the inflation, yeah, of course there was a cost, but somebody had to bear the cost of these very real shocks.

271
00:27:44,380 --> 00:27:49,380
[SPEAKER_00] And this is the higher inflation was just one way that it was born.

272
00:27:49,380 --> 00:27:54,380
[SPEAKER_00] In terms of, let's see, I'll move on cognizant of time here.

273
00:27:54,380 --> 00:28:01,380
[SPEAKER_00] In terms of the debt to GDP ratio, I think I was happy to see Lucas, I think, plotted the same thing.

274
00:28:01,380 --> 00:28:06,380
[SPEAKER_00] The blue line there, the orange line is the conventional measure of debt to GDP.

275
00:28:06,380 --> 00:28:11,380
[SPEAKER_00] We see that it was stable at about 100 prior to the shocks.

276
00:28:11,380 --> 00:28:13,380
[SPEAKER_00] It was elevated substantially.

277
00:28:13,380 --> 00:28:20,380
[SPEAKER_00] It has subsequently come down a little bit primarily because of the inflation, and in part because of the real recovery.

278
00:28:20,380 --> 00:28:25,380
[SPEAKER_00] I'd like to look at the blue line, and Lucas did this as well.

279
00:28:25,380 --> 00:28:30,380
[SPEAKER_00] This is the market value of marketable treasury securities as a ratio of GDP.

280
00:28:30,380 --> 00:28:39,380
[SPEAKER_00] The difference here is the marketable, the total debt overstates the debt because much of this debt is held by intra-governmental agencies.

281
00:28:39,380 --> 00:28:44,380
[SPEAKER_00] And the marketable debt is primarily that held by the private sector.

282
00:28:44,380 --> 00:28:54,380
[SPEAKER_00] And we see that the debt to GDP ratio in the blue line is coming down much more rapidly, in part because of the inflation, but also in part because of the higher interest rates.

283
00:28:54,380 --> 00:29:03,380
[SPEAKER_00] And so the question is, like, if you believe in mean reversion here, you might be asking, like, how much further does inflation have to go up?

284
00:29:03,380 --> 00:29:11,380
[SPEAKER_00] How much further do interest rates have to come down to kind of make this debt to GDP ratio come back down to kind of its steady state level?

285
00:29:11,380 --> 00:29:15,380
[SPEAKER_00] Probably not much is what this diagram is suggesting.

286
00:29:15,380 --> 00:29:16,380
[SPEAKER_00] Okay.

287
00:29:16,380 --> 00:29:19,380
[SPEAKER_00] Let me conclude about the future path of inflation.

288
00:29:19,380 --> 00:29:23,380
[SPEAKER_00] I think that, you know, first let me comment briefly on Fed policy.

289
00:29:23,380 --> 00:29:35,380
[SPEAKER_00] You know, I'm still very close with a number of the people there, and my former boss, Jim Bullard, and also Chris Waller, the Board of Governors now.

290
00:29:35,380 --> 00:29:38,380
[SPEAKER_00] I mean, this is not even, this is not private information.

291
00:29:38,380 --> 00:29:46,380
[SPEAKER_00] This is from their public speech, as they say, that as long as inflation remains above target, and as long as the labor market remains okay,

292
00:29:46,380 --> 00:29:50,380
[SPEAKER_00] I mean, we're going to have to expect further rate increases.

293
00:29:50,380 --> 00:29:52,380
[SPEAKER_00] This is just what they're saying.

294
00:29:52,380 --> 00:29:54,380
[SPEAKER_00] The policy will be data dependent, of course.

295
00:29:54,380 --> 00:29:59,380
[SPEAKER_00] It will depend on how things evolve, but the Fed has a dual mandate.

296
00:29:59,380 --> 00:30:07,380
[SPEAKER_00] And notwithstanding the recent, you know, reverberations in the banking sector, I think, by and large, given the way the data looks right now,

297
00:30:07,380 --> 00:30:14,380
[SPEAKER_00] I'd be expecting further hikes, although probably not as dramatic as what we've seen so far.

298
00:30:14,380 --> 00:30:21,380
[SPEAKER_00] And barring any further shocks, you know, I mean, I think, I have to admit, I was always on team transitory.

299
00:30:21,380 --> 00:30:23,380
[SPEAKER_00] I still am on team transitory.

300
00:30:23,380 --> 00:30:26,380
[SPEAKER_00] I think team transitory was largely correct.

301
00:30:26,380 --> 00:30:31,380
[SPEAKER_00] The energy price shock was a supply shock that was transitory.

302
00:30:31,380 --> 00:30:37,380
[SPEAKER_00] The fiscal stimulus, at least in the United States, was large, but it basically ended by the end of 2021.

303
00:30:37,380 --> 00:30:40,380
[SPEAKER_00] And it's just continuing to work its way through the system.

304
00:30:40,380 --> 00:30:47,380
[SPEAKER_00] So, but whether, I think the big question is not whether inflation is going to continue to come down.

305
00:30:47,380 --> 00:30:54,380
[SPEAKER_00] I think the big question is, of course, is whether it's going to come back to its 2% target anytime soon.

306
00:30:54,380 --> 00:30:57,380
[SPEAKER_00] And here, I think it's very hard to say.

307
00:30:57,380 --> 00:30:59,380
[SPEAKER_00] I don't think any of us can say.

308
00:30:59,380 --> 00:31:06,380
[SPEAKER_00] My own view, I take a very fiscalist approach to inflation, to the determination of long-run inflation.

309
00:31:06,380 --> 00:31:08,380
[SPEAKER_00] And to me, fiscal policy is what's critical here.

310
00:31:08,380 --> 00:31:13,380
[SPEAKER_00] Fiscal policy, though, depends on unfolding geopolitical events.

311
00:31:13,380 --> 00:31:20,380
[SPEAKER_00] And, you know, the growing Sino-American conflict here is a pretty worrying sign.

312
00:31:20,380 --> 00:31:27,380
[SPEAKER_00] These wars, whether they're hot wars or cold wars, put fiscal pressures on governments, the United States in particular.

313
00:31:27,380 --> 00:31:32,380
[SPEAKER_00] And these fiscal pressures are going to be inflationary pressures.

314
00:31:32,380 --> 00:31:37,380
[SPEAKER_00] And there's even the question of whether it's desirable to let inflation come down to 2%.

315
00:31:37,380 --> 00:31:48,380
[SPEAKER_00] Because maybe a little inflation tax is not a bad way to help finance this, you know, the global policeman role of the United States.

316
00:31:48,380 --> 00:31:57,380
[SPEAKER_00] It's our allies that are using our treasuries extensively for a variety of reasons perhaps are chipping in a little bit here as well through this slightly higher inflation tax.

317
00:31:57,380 --> 00:31:58,380
[SPEAKER_00] I don't know.

318
00:31:58,380 --> 00:32:00,380
[SPEAKER_00] But that's where I'll end it.

319
00:32:00,380 --> 00:32:03,380
[SPEAKER_00] Thank you very much for your attention.

320
00:32:03,380 --> 00:32:05,380
[SPEAKER_00] Hvala.

321
00:32:33,380 --> 00:32:55,559
[SPEAKER_02] Good afternoon everybody. Can I just start by also thanking Boris and the organizers for inviting me to this conference and for hosting this conference in this venue? My first visit to Croatia and my first visit obviously to Dubrovnik. Delighted to be here.

322
00:32:55,559 --> 00:33:17,740
[SPEAKER_02] And thank you both David and to Paul for their comments and I look forward to the discussion that we're going to have afterwards. My focus is going to be on the interaction between monetary and fiscal policy and I suppose it's a bit of a truism to say that the current macroeconomic environment is a complex one for policymakers.

323
00:33:17,740 --> 00:33:30,299
[SPEAKER_02] The outlook for inflation continues to be too high and we're continuing to project it to stay too high for too long which means there is more ground for central banks to cover.

324
00:33:30,740 --> 00:33:42,740
[SPEAKER_02] Monetary policy must be brought to levels sufficiently restrictive to bring inflation back to target and as Philip told us yesterday, in a timely manner.

325
00:33:42,740 --> 00:33:57,740
[SPEAKER_02] But fiscal policy must also adjust its priorities to tackle the challenges of the major economic transitions involved in climate change, in aging populations and in geo-economic fragmentation.

326
00:33:57,740 --> 00:34:04,740
[SPEAKER_02] But the increased cost of living does generate political pressures that could slow this necessary adjustment.

327
00:34:04,740 --> 00:34:12,739
[SPEAKER_02] As I think most of you know, monetary policy fights inflation mainly through two channels.

328
00:34:12,739 --> 00:34:20,739
[SPEAKER_02] First, by reducing aggregate demand and second, by anchoring the expectation of future inflation to its target.

329
00:34:20,739 --> 00:34:30,739
[SPEAKER_02] And at times like this, when inflation is already far too high, expansive fiscal policy risks undermining both of these mechanisms.

330
00:34:30,739 --> 00:34:39,739
[SPEAKER_02] Primarily by increasing aggregate demand, but also by signalling that the government is counteracting the effects of policies aimed at reducing inflation.

331
00:34:39,739 --> 00:34:42,739
[SPEAKER_02] Potentially increasing inflation expectations.

332
00:34:42,739 --> 00:34:52,739
[SPEAKER_02] And that's why I and others have previously called for cost of living supports to be targeted, to be temporary and to be tailored.

333
00:34:52,739 --> 00:35:08,739
[SPEAKER_02] Fiscal policy can be a major force for good when it provides the stable foundation for a thriving economy, but it can also cause great harm by adding to inflationary pressures, which would inevitably call for an even stronger monetary policy response.

334
00:35:08,739 --> 00:35:13,739
[SPEAKER_02] Monetary and fiscal policies need to work together to shore up macroeconomic stability.

335
00:35:13,739 --> 00:35:19,739
[SPEAKER_02] And the coherence of monetary and fiscal policy is essential for that stability.

336
00:35:19,739 --> 00:35:28,739
[SPEAKER_02] During the pandemic, we saw how powerfully combined monetary and fiscal efforts helped our economies to quickly get out of recession.

337
00:35:28,739 --> 00:35:39,739
[SPEAKER_02] But it is also not only during downturns that monetary and fiscal policy need to coordinate their actions to effectively complement each other.

338
00:35:39,739 --> 00:35:44,739
[SPEAKER_02] An adequate policy mix is just as essential at times like this when we must fight inflation.

339
00:35:44,739 --> 00:36:07,739
[SPEAKER_02] At a minimum, fiscal policy should avoid directly contributing to the building up of inflationary pressures, but preferably fiscal authorities should support the disinflation effort by gradually bringing down high public debt while also calibrating their policies to make our economy more productive and to avoid adverse distributional effects.

340
00:36:07,739 --> 00:36:18,739
[SPEAKER_02] Monetary policy cannot be targeted and tailored in the way that fiscal policy can, nor does it have the mandate to address those distributional issues.

341
00:36:18,739 --> 00:36:29,739
[SPEAKER_02] But monetary tightening could be complemented with changes in the composition of fiscal spending, where the available resources are better targeted to those most in need of support.

342
00:36:29,739 --> 00:36:35,739
[SPEAKER_02] Inflation imposes a burden on the poorest households disproportionately.

343
00:36:35,739 --> 00:36:42,739
[SPEAKER_02] And in the short term, monetary tightening may add to this burden by constraining aggregate demand and labour market conditions.

344
00:36:42,739 --> 00:36:52,739
[SPEAKER_02] And a better composition of fiscal spending is essential to protect the economy from the risk of poverty and excessive income inequality.

345
00:36:52,739 --> 00:36:58,739
[SPEAKER_02] The fiscal policies that we are seeing in action are not sufficiently adhering to these principles.

346
00:36:58,739 --> 00:37:10,739
[SPEAKER_02] In the Euro area, the fiscal response to the energy crisis has been large, amounting to nearly 2% of GDP in 2022, with a similar figure expected in 2023.

347
00:37:10,739 --> 00:37:27,739
[SPEAKER_02] And while difficult to classify precisely, about half of the total support in the Euro area over the 2022-23 period is assessed as affecting prices directly via lower marginal costs of energy consumption, with income measures making up the remainder.

348
00:37:27,739 --> 00:37:36,739
[SPEAKER_02] Only about 12% of the total support is estimated to be targeted at vulnerable households.

349
00:37:36,739 --> 00:37:41,739
[SPEAKER_02] And to a smaller extent, firms directly affected by higher energy prices.

350
00:37:41,739 --> 00:37:48,739
[SPEAKER_02] And such untargeted spending is increasing demand and directly contributing to inflationary pressures.

351
00:37:48,739 --> 00:37:59,739
[SPEAKER_02] Price measures and energy price discounts may have contained prices initially, but they are costly to the budget and prevent often necessary demand adjustments.

352
00:37:59,739 --> 00:38:09,739
[SPEAKER_02] Most importantly, by contributing to higher and more persistent inflation over the medium term, their longer term effectiveness is questionable at best.

353
00:38:09,739 --> 00:38:12,739
[SPEAKER_02] The outlook for public finances can rapidly change.

354
00:38:12,739 --> 00:38:25,739
[SPEAKER_02] Monetary tightening has not yet adversely affected public debt sustainability, which is largely due to the initial positive impact that inflation tends to have on the public finances.

355
00:38:25,739 --> 00:38:40,739
[SPEAKER_02] But together with the higher revenues, a rise in nominal GDP, owing in large part to high inflation, has led to significant decreases in the jet-to-DGP ratio that had reached historically high levels after the pandemic.

356
00:38:40,739 --> 00:38:43,739
[SPEAKER_02] Deficits, however, continue to be too high.

357
00:38:43,739 --> 00:38:52,739
[SPEAKER_02] In the fourth quarter of 2022, the deficit to GDP ratio stood at 4.7% in the Euro area.

358
00:38:52,739 --> 00:39:07,739
[SPEAKER_02] So, it grew compared to the previous quarter because increases in total expenditure exceeded those in total revenue, which shows that the initial positive effects of inflation and public finances can easily revert over time.

359
00:39:07,739 --> 00:39:14,739
[SPEAKER_02] Spending measures can intensify, offsetting or even overtaking the benefits on the revenue side.

360
00:39:14,739 --> 00:39:24,739
[SPEAKER_02] So far, while government bond yields are obviously rising in response to policy rate increases, sovereign spreads have remained relatively compressed.

361
00:39:24,739 --> 00:39:37,739
[SPEAKER_02] However, with growth expected to reduce, government interest payments increase, and the central bank progress in its quantitative tightening, the sustainability of public debt cannot be taken for granted.

362
00:39:37,739 --> 00:39:45,739
[SPEAKER_02] The least desirable scenario is one in which markets start questioning sovereigns' credit worthiness again.

363
00:39:45,739 --> 00:39:55,739
[SPEAKER_02] In Europe, we know only too well the financial distress that can result in such cases, and the deep and long-lasting scars it can leave to the economy.

364
00:39:55,739 --> 00:40:09,739
[SPEAKER_02] Sound management of public finances firmly based on counter-cyclicality, debt sustainability, and the promotion of growth can help avoid adverse outcomes like this in the future.

365
00:40:09,739 --> 00:40:15,739
[SPEAKER_02] We should also not underestimate the damage such episodes do to trust in the Euro itself.

366
00:40:15,739 --> 00:40:25,739
[SPEAKER_02] Appropriate governance could help to put public finances on a sound and long-term footing and reduce the tensions between fiscal and monetary policies.

367
00:40:25,739 --> 00:40:27,739
[SPEAKER_02] These tensions are not new.

368
00:40:27,739 --> 00:40:40,739
[SPEAKER_02] Even in the short history of the Euro area, our macroeconomic performance has suffered from fiscal pro-cyclicality as well as from episodes of fiscal sustainability problems in some countries.

369
00:40:40,739 --> 00:40:52,739
[SPEAKER_02] Sustainable fiscal positions and counter-cyclical fiscal policy are necessary conditions for the realisation of price stability and macroeconomic stability.

370
00:40:52,739 --> 00:41:00,739
[SPEAKER_02] And yet, the macroeconomic governance framework that was in place over the first two decades of the Euro proved insufficient to promote them.

371
00:41:00,739 --> 00:41:06,739
[SPEAKER_02] The importance of making the framework a better fit for the task cannot be overemphasised.

372
00:41:06,739 --> 00:41:16,739
